I've lived in Alabama my whole life, I enjoy that there is plenty of places to just get away from people, Huntsville is a great city and I like the job opportunities. However, I would say there are some cultural and political problems within the state, A large minority of the state boasts their lack of education/reasoning skills, many of these people are good people but I believe politics have consumed a majority of their beliefs as simple things such as education have been completely polarized. The partisanship expressed by many inhabitants is unhealthy to the state, I even have a large majority of my family that will call you a communist for supporting any policy that isn't a Republican view. I believe this severely hampers the states ability to flourish as the state is slowly becoming an echo chamber of anti-democrat views(I'm talking views that don't even have to help our citizens but can simply harm non-republicans). I do not believe either party is 100% correct on every policy and I believe there are many arcane and failed policies retained by the state just because the alternative my be seen as democratic policy. For example, I believe that the criminalization of marijuana is a failed policy as it has done nothing to benefit the lives of the citizens of the state and has only proved to benefit the revenue system of the courts. Having grown up here my whole life I can with 100% certainty say that the current system has not dampered the use of marijuana(even among teens as in highschool it was easier to purchase marijuana than alcohol(p.s. Criminals don't care who they sell to, Businesses do)) We have severely hampered all the tax revenue that comes from the sale of marijuana because it now goes unreported. I feel there are many more examples where the state has chose to maintain the old laws/stances that can easily be shown to be unhelpful and sometimes detrimental to the population. These problems can be fixed but only through the election of members of the society that want to see the state flourish and not members who want a career and a paycheck.

Alabama is unfortunately very regressive and I find the expectations regarding everyday quality of life, health, and customer service to be devastatingly slow. There are points in time in which the residents make you feel bad for asking them to do their jobs. There are little to no expectations for improvement and if any are brought up, the entire idea of "change" causes ignorant hysteria.  I hate to be the person who brings up COVID, but there were times when every one of my friends and I had emailed the president separately with constructive criticism. It feels as if the reputation within these communities and its image is more important than the actual significance of what each decision means for the people living there. For instance, while police are handing out tickets to students on the strip left and right for not wearing masks, perhaps instead of targeting a very financially, emotionally, and mentally stressed demographic of college students, it would be smarter and more efficient to close down University Dr. (which is easily done on game days) and allow restaurants and bars to seat people outside or in the street? As I mentioned, there is no authentic concern for students or our wellbeing, what's important is that it looks like there is a concern to bystanders. Things seem to be handed to residents in Alabama compared to in other states where there are certifications and training involved. For instance, the process of acquiring one's driver's license is little to none here in Alabama, whereas in Illinois you have to not only take a driving class but also have a permit for lots of time and pass a written and driving exam. The difference in driving on the road is extremely noticeable in these two different states, as well as the overall attitudes of the people and their different rates of innovation as a result of their lower or higher expectations for their community members.

More than just an issue with Alabama Iâ€™d say that political polarization is something that is plaguing the US as a whole. Iâ€™d love to see a nice skate park, a Trader Joeâ€™s, maybe even a vegan restaurant in Tuscaloosa! Even unique landmarks and bridges, (on a larger scale than Vulcan) could help with retention, being a state where locals can be tourists!! A large amusement park, could be such a hoot!! Iâ€™d love to see more emphasis on hiking and the outdoors from a ~granola-sunny-day-hiker~ Standpoint and less marketing in the hunting industry (which I acknowledge is pretty integral to society and the market here, it is in TN too). I donâ€™t want Alabama to be a majorly liberal state, but I think the openness and outspoken support of gay communities, artists, folk and indie music is attractive to young people. Itâ€™s why I believe North Carolina and Texas have had such success with their retention and population. They have cities like Asheville, Raleigh, Charleston as well as Austin and Houston. I think from a marketing standpoint Alabama should focus on bringing in new and improved â€œstate-of-the-artâ€ facilities, venues, architecture, and gardens. Instead of focusing on the history and how far weâ€™ve come (which is still very important to acknowledge), taking an approach to enjoy the natural beauty of the state and visit newly built interesting places would draw a lot of people to want to come and then stay here. Another VERY large factor is the job market here is not fantastic, but more so than that is the transportation here isnâ€™t connected to a lot of other cities. I think it would benefit the state enormously would be to help finance a connection of the High-speed railway in the US starting in Mobile/Gulf Shores and moving upward into Montgomery, then to Birmingham, with possible stops or small scale connectors to Auburn and Tuscaloosa and then have a central Alabama station to take a train up through Nashville with a fairly straight shot to Chicago or take the route NE through TN Smokey mountain area (Chattanooga, Knoxville, Bristol) to connect to the railway already existing in Washington DC.
